The period is a long one. It begins with an ‘is’ clause, absque soret te=si sine te foret, then follows the apodosis distraxissent &c- The reason for the statement is given in ita &c. (which might be replaced by a nam clause), and ita is followed first by descriptive imperf„ then by hist. infin. Finally, to couple the whole period more closely together, the original protasis is repeated in a different and fuller form—ni tua pax propitia soret praesto is absque foret te ‘writ large.’ Cf. the period Pers. 836—840.
